En la columna otras, se incluy la informacin del Ministerio de Defensa y sus Unidades Adscritas (INOCAR-IGM), el Comando Conjunto y su Unidad Orgnica (HOSPITAL MILITAR).

Defensa, consecuencia de la centralizacin de la nmina en el ejercicio 2014, y figuran en
la columna Otras fuerzas militares.

Los gastos militares se refieren a todos los recursos financieros que un Estado
gasta en los usos y funciones de sus fuerzas militares. La informacin sobre los gastos
militares corresponde a un desembolso real a precios corrientes y en moneda
nacional.

Se invita a los Estados Miembros a que consideren la posibilidad de explicar o
aclarar, segn proceda, las cifras presentadas en los formularios de informe (por
ejemplo, sobre los gastos militares como porcentaje del producto interno bruto, los
cambios importantes con respecto a informes anteriores y circunstancias especiales).
Al final de la matriz se agrega un campo titulado Observaciones explicativas. Las
notas explicativas tambin se pueden proporcionar en un documento aparte adjunto
a la matriz.

Se invita a los Estados Miembros a que consideren la posibilidad de
proporcionar, segn proceda, informacin fctica y probatoria adicional (por ejemplo,
listas y enlaces en la web de los principales documentos a disposicin del pblico y
material de referencia que refleja su poltica de defensa, sus estrategias y doctrinas
militares y Libros Blancos). La informacin adicional y los documentos respectivos,
de haberlos, pueden incluirse como anexos al informe nacional.

Todas las fuerzas militares de un Estado que no estn incluidas en las columnas 1
a 4 y otras fuerzas armadas de ese Estado que, debido a su estructura, equipo o
misin, pueden llevar a cabo operaciones militares.

Se deben incluir tanto las misiones encomendadas y dirigidas por las Naciones
Unidas como otras misiones encomendadas por las Naciones Unidas.

La participacin de los contingentes y el equipo militares de un Estado en
actividades para ayudar a los civiles en casos de desastres naturales y otras
emergencias de carcter no militar, si son parte de los gastos militares. Dado que
parte de esos gastos tambin se pueden asentar en otros Grupos de fuerzas, se
recomienda que se formulen explicaciones adicionales en Observaciones
explicativas.

Se deben incluir los pagos directos por los servicios actuales y futuros hechos al
personal as como otros gastos por concepto de remuneraciones al personal
efectuados por el empleador, tales como impuestos, segn proceda, pensiones (si son
parte del presupuesto militar) y otras contribuciones.

Se debe incluir la compra de alimentos, ropa, productos derivados del petrleo,
materiales de capacitacin (con exclusin de pertrechos y municiones) y suministros
mdicos.

Se deben incluir tanto los servicios por contrata como la compra de piezas,
herramientas y materiales para la reparacin y el mantenimiento de equipo e
instalaciones militares, incluidos los almacenes y depsitos.

Se deben incluir los gastos para diversos tipos de servicios prestados por
terceros, tales como gastos de viaje, de correo, de impresin y de otro tipo, as como
contratistas civiles y privados.

Se deben incluir las inversiones considerables en la adquisicin de armas y
equipo militar, y la construccin y la modernizacin sustancial de las instalaciones
militares que aumentan las capacidades de combate, mejoran la calidad e influyen en
el rendimiento.

Se debe incluir el total de gastos por concepto de otras fuerzas militares, la
administracin de apoyo y mandos centrales, la cooperacin militar, la ayuda a los
civiles y los gastos no distribuidos.

2018
Whereever and whenever possible the Netherlands" defence organization will adopt NATO doctrine as national doctrine.
Defense reinforces its digital resilience and the ability to perform cyber operations. The deployability of the Dutch armed forces and the effectiveness in the digital domain
can thus be increased. This increase comes on top of the one-off investment of  17 million for the years 2017 up to and including 2019 that the Cabinet decided earlier in
2017. In 2017, the government also decided that with  20 million per 2018, extra money would be available for the border guard task.

The information and figures contained in this report were originally compiled in September '19 based on the Defense Financial budget report 2019, which still
has to be approved by Parliament. In the meantime the Cabinet has decided in putting extra money into Defense. Structurally, this involves an additional  162
million per year. The amount goes up to  461 million and a total of  1.5 billion until 2024. The intentions of the cabinet have been presented in the Spring
Memorandum that was presented to the Lower House on 27 May 2019. With the extra money, investments are made in personnel and a next step is taken in the
realization of agreements made within the NATO context. Attribution of extra money to Defense shows that Defense is one of the top priorities of the
Netherlands. GDP percentages on Defence expenditures are projected by the Netherlands Bureau for Economic Policy Analysis (CPB) based on the foreseen
growth rates for the coming years will look as follows: 2019 2020 2021 2022 2023 2024 1.41% 1.43% 1.46% 1.42% 1.38% 1,37% NATO's budget figures for
the Netherlands are based on the growth rates of the IMF / OECD and thus have a different pattern. These figures are published in the NATO burden sharing
report of June 2019. 2019 2020 2021 2022 2023 2024 1.35% 1.38% 1.41% 1.35% 1.31% 1,30% The intentions towards the additional investments and
increase of the Defense budget were announced in the National Plan for NATO in December 2018. This was done on the basis of agreements from 2014 to
distribute the burden within the NATO Alliance more evenly and to strengthen the effectiveness of NATO and the EU. Where ever and whenever possible the
Netherlands' defence organization will adopt NATO agreed doctrine as national doctrine.

In the first quarter of 2020, the Netherlands, like the rest of the world, was struck by the Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) pandemic. Developments associated with COVID-19 had and will have a serious impact on plans and policy and on their implementation. Planned (international) exercises have been discontinued, changed or cancelled altogether and various activities have been discontinued or will not be carried out. Financial obligations associated with these activities will of course be affected as a result. In addition, the Defence organisation will be assigned tasks to combat the crisis and military and civilian personnel will be tasked with supporting the national crisis team and handling emergencies.
We will face unexpected crises more often in the future. The world is in a constant state of flux, and this greatly affects the focus and structure of the MoD and our national and inter-national partners. We therefore agreed in 2014 that, in the following ten years, defence spending would increase to 2% of our gross domestic product (GDP). This will make it possible for us to develop into a military organisation that contributes its fair share to NATO objectives. This process of growth to strengthen the foundation of NATO in concert with our partners has been set out in the national plan. This plan shows how defence spending will rise to 2% of GDP in the period until 2024. If all the allies do so, then we can defend our shared freedom and security. The Netherlands has not been meeting this target, and therefore our allies expect more from us. We are being called to account internationally. With a defence budget of approx 1.33% of GDP, the Netherlands falls below the European average (1.58% in 2019).

In the first quarter of 2020, the Netherlands, like the rest of the world, was struck by the Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19 pandemic). Developments associated with COVID-19 had a serious impact on the budget. Now that society is opening up gradually, COVID-19 measures will be lifted and it will take time to return to the original level of operation. Arrears must be made up. The submitted budget figures were compiled by the outgoing Rutte III cabinet. This cabinet offered to resign on 15 January 2021, due to the hard conclusions of the parliamentary investigation of the childcare allowance. As caretaker, the cabinet worked in a demissionary status over the elections of 17 March 2021 and nearly a year after resignation cabinet Rutte IV took office on January 10, 2022.Due to the changing security situation in the world and growing instability, the new cabinet is in the process of making urgent financial adjustments to contributions to defence. These financial adjustments are reflected in the Coalition Agreement, which emphasizes the importance of investments in defence. The structural increase in the budget will enable the Ministry of Defence to take a major step forward. This is also urgently needed and will lead to a substantial improvement in the operational readiness of the armed forces. This will have an effect on the budget in 2022. Attribution of extra money to Defence shows that Defence is one of the top priorities of the Netherlands. Wherever and whenever possible the Netherlands' defence organization will adopt NATO agreed doctrine as national doctrine.
